<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="197" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,213,706]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,427,213,238]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Diagnosis. Male imago</emphasis>
(Adapted from 
<bibRefCitation author="Falcao, J. N. &amp; Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N." box="[616,828,213,238]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="39 - 46" refId="ref6159" refString="Falcao, J. N., Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N. (2010) The adults of Harpagobaetis Mol and Tomedontus Lugo-Ortiz and McCafferty (Ephemeroptera: Baetidae) with notes on the nymphal stage. Zootaxa, 2530 (1), 39 - 46. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2530.1.4" type="journal article" year="2010">
Falcão 
<emphasis box="[701,752,213,238]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
). 1) forewing with paired marginal intercalary veins (Fig. 10a in 
<bibRefCitation author="Falcao, J. N. &amp; Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N." box="[293,505,249,274]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="39 - 46" refId="ref6159" refString="Falcao, J. N., Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N. (2010) The adults of Harpagobaetis Mol and Tomedontus Lugo-Ortiz and McCafferty (Ephemeroptera: Baetidae) with notes on the nymphal stage. Zootaxa, 2530 (1), 39 - 46. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2530.1.4" type="journal article" year="2010">
Falcão 
<emphasis box="[377,428,249,274]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
); 2) hind wing present, with two complete longitudinal veins (Figs 10b and 
<quantity box="[1379,1436,249,274]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.794" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" unit="in" value="11.0">11 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Falcao, J. N. &amp; Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N." box="[151,362,285,310]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="39 - 46" refId="ref6159" refString="Falcao, J. N., Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N. (2010) The adults of Harpagobaetis Mol and Tomedontus Lugo-Ortiz and McCafferty (Ephemeroptera: Baetidae) with notes on the nymphal stage. Zootaxa, 2530 (1), 39 - 46. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2530.1.4" type="journal article" year="2010">
Falcão 
<emphasis box="[235,286,285,310]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
); 3) costal projection of hind wing pointed, placed in the basal third of anterior margin, cross veins absent (Figs 10b and 
<quantity box="[470,528,321,346]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.794" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" unit="in" value="11.0">11 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Falcao, J. N. &amp; Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N." box="[538,751,321,346]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="39 - 46" refId="ref6159" refString="Falcao, J. N., Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N. (2010) The adults of Harpagobaetis Mol and Tomedontus Lugo-Ortiz and McCafferty (Ephemeroptera: Baetidae) with notes on the nymphal stage. Zootaxa, 2530 (1), 39 - 46. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2530.1.4" type="journal article" year="2010">
Falcão 
<emphasis box="[622,673,321,346]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
); 4) forceps three-segmented, segment I with bulbous base, segment III long, about 3.0× as long as wide (Fig. 
<quantity box="[755,816,357,382]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.048" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" unit="in" value="12.0">12 in</quantity>
<bibRefCitation author="Falcao, J. N. &amp; Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N." box="[827,1044,357,382]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" pagination="39 - 46" refId="ref6159" refString="Falcao, J. N., Salles, F. F. &amp; Hamada, N. (2010) The adults of Harpagobaetis Mol and Tomedontus Lugo-Ortiz and McCafferty (Ephemeroptera: Baetidae) with notes on the nymphal stage. Zootaxa, 2530 (1), 39 - 46. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 2530.1.4" type="journal article" year="2010">
Falcão 
<emphasis box="[912,965,357,382]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2010
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1066,1256,357,382]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Mature Nymph</emphasis>
(Adapted from 
<bibRefCitation author="Dominguez, E. &amp; Molineri, C. M. &amp; Pescador, M. &amp; Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C." box="[151,418,393,418]" pageId="2" pageNumber="197" refId="ref6106" refString="Dominguez, E., Molineri, C. M., Pescador, M., Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C. (2006) Ephemeroptera of South America. Aquatic Biodiversity of Latin America. Fol. 2. Pensoft, Sofia, 646 pp." type="book" year="2006">
Domínguez 
<emphasis box="[291,343,393,418]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
). 1) antenna 1.5–2.0 × as long as head capsule (adapted); 2) frons without frontal keels (new); 3) clypeus reduced in length (
<figureCitation box="[568,656,429,454]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. A. dorsal habitus, B. details of body (dorsal habitus); C. details of abdominal terga and gills; D. frontal view of head; E. lateral view of head; F. frontal view of head, details of mouthparts." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622788/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
) (new); 4) labrum wider than long, width more than 2.0 × the length (
<figureCitation box="[159,246,465,490]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. A. dorsal habitus, B. details of body (dorsal habitus); C. details of abdominal terga and gills; D. frontal view of head; E. lateral view of head; F. frontal view of head, details of mouthparts." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622788/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 1D</figureCitation>
) (adapted); 5) superlinguae of hypopharynx with lateral expansion (
<figureCitation box="[1010,1098,465,490]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1987,2009]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,204,1962]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[163,1425,193,1977]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. Holotype. A. hypopharynx (left v.v., right d.v.); B. labium (left v.v., right d.v.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622795/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
) (adapted); 6) mandibles long and narrow, incisor completely fused (
<figureCitation box="[578,714,501,526]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1713,1735]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,225,1648]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[150,1436,225,1663]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. Holotype. A. antenna (medial third); B. labrum (left v.v., right d.v.); C. detail of distal margin of labrum (left v.v., right d.v.); D. left mandible (d.v.); E. maxilla (d.v.); F. right mandible (d.v)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622793/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Figs 3D, 3F</figureCitation>
) (adapted); 7) mandibles with molar shaped like an incisor (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1713,1735]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,225,1648]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[150,1436,225,1663]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. Holotype. A. antenna (medial third); B. labrum (left v.v., right d.v.); C. detail of distal margin of labrum (left v.v., right d.v.); D. left mandible (d.v.); E. maxilla (d.v.); F. right mandible (d.v)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622793/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Figs 3D, 3F</figureCitation>
) (adapted); 8) canines of galea-lacinia long and slender (
<figureCitation box="[876,961,537,562]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1713,1735]" captionTargetBox="[155,1426,225,1648]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[150,1436,225,1663]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 3. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. Holotype. A. antenna (medial third); B. labrum (left v.v., right d.v.); C. detail of distal margin of labrum (left v.v., right d.v.); D. left mandible (d.v.); E. maxilla (d.v.); F. right mandible (d.v)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622793/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
) (adapted); 9) labium elongated (
<figureCitation box="[1341,1428,537,562]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1987,2009]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,204,1962]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[163,1425,193,1977]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. Holotype. A. hypopharynx (left v.v., right d.v.); B. labium (left v.v., right d.v.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622795/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
) (adapted); 10) inner margin of labial palp segment II without distomedial projection (
<figureCitation box="[1111,1199,573,598]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1987,2009]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,204,1962]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[163,1425,193,1977]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. Holotype. A. hypopharynx (left v.v., right d.v.); B. labium (left v.v., right d.v.)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622795/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
); 11) hind wing pads present (new); 12) tarsal claws with two rows of triangular denticles increasing in size distally (adapted); 13) surface of abdominal terga without scales or scale-like setae (new); 14) gills on segments I–VII (
<figureCitation box="[1259,1345,645,670]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. A. dorsal habitus, B. details of body (dorsal habitus); C. details of abdominal terga and gills; D. frontal view of head; E. lateral view of head; F. frontal view of head, details of mouthparts." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622788/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 1C</figureCitation>
) (new); 15) paracercus as long as cerci (
<figureCitation box="[509,598,681,706]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1969,1991]" captionTargetBox="[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[281,1312,193,1960]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Harpagobaetis brigada sp. nov. A. dorsal habitus, B. details of body (dorsal habitus); C. details of abdominal terga and gills; D. frontal view of head; E. lateral view of head; F. frontal view of head, details of mouthparts." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2622788/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="197">Fig. 1A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
